<div class="content-section">
    <div class="header">
        <h2>‚öóÔ∏è Understanding Metal Pollution in Water ‚Äî FAQs</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <span>‚öóÔ∏è What Are Metal Indices Of Water?</span>
                <span class="icon">‚ñº</span>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-answer">
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 5%; animation-delay: 0s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 25%; animation-delay: -1s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 75%; animation-delay: -2s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 95%; animation-delay: -3s;"></div>

                <p>Metal indices are special numbers that help scientists and the public understand the level of harmful
                    metals present in water. Metals like lead, arsenic, cadmium, and chromium can be dangerous to both
                    human health and the environment when found in high amounts. Instead of checking each metal
                    separately, scientists use these indices to combine all the information into one or two
                    easy-to-understand values. This makes it simpler to know whether the water is safe to drink or if it
                    needs treatment.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <span>üìä Why Do We Calculate These Indices?</span>
                <span class="icon">‚ñº</span>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-answer">
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 15%; animation-delay: -0.5s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 65%; animation-delay: -1.5s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 85%; animation-delay: -2.5s;"></div>

                <p>Calculating metal indices gives a clear picture of water pollution that would otherwise require
                    checking many different numbers. For example, each harmful metal has its own safe level. If we check
                    them individually, it can be confusing. Metal indices like HEI, PLI, and NPI combine these values
                    into a single score. This helps scientists, policymakers, and communities quickly compare water
                    quality across different places and times. It also makes it easier to detect changes in pollution
                    levels and take the necessary steps to protect health and the environment.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <span>üîç What Do Key Metal Indices Mean?</span>
                <span class="icon">‚ñº</span>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-answer">
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 20%; animation-delay: -0.8s;"></div>
                <div class="animated-water-drop" style="left: 50%; animation-delay: -1.8s;"></div>

                <p><b>HEI (Heavy Metal Evaluation Index)</b> measures the combined risk from all harmful metals in the
                    water. It gives a single number that shows the overall danger level.</p>
                <p><b>PLI (Pollution Load Index)</b> works like a ‚Äúpollution scorecard‚Äù ‚Äî it shows how polluted the
